const INTERVIEW_DATA = {
  dita: {
    label:'DITA',
    icon:'📄',
    questions:[
      {q:'What does DITA stand for and who created it?',a:'Darwin Information Typing Architecture. Created by IBM\'s Information Architecture team (led by Michael Priestley) in 2001, donated to OASIS in 2004, where it became an open standard. The name reflects three principles: Darwin (content evolves via specialization), Information Typing (content is classified into types), Architecture (a comprehensive system).'},
      {q:'What are the three base DITA topic types and when do you use each?',a:'(1) Concept — answers "What is it?" or "How does it work?" Used for system descriptions, background knowledge, definitions. (2) Task — answers "How do I do it?" Contains prereq, context, ordered steps (cmd), result, postreq. Used for procedures. (3) Reference — contains lookup information: specifications, parameters, part numbers, error codes. Users query it rather than read it linearly.'},
      {q:'What is a DITA map and what does it contain?',a:'A DITA map is an XML file that assembles individual topic files into a publication. It contains topicref elements pointing to topic files, establishing hierarchy and navigation order. Maps also contain keydefs (variable definitions), topicmeta (map-level metadata), and can contain ditavalref for branch filtering. Maps produce the Table of Contents and publication assembly.'},
      {q:'Explain the difference between a ditamap and a bookmap.',a:'Both assemble topics into publications. ditamap is for general-purpose documentation (help systems, web portals) using nested topicrefs. bookmap is a specialization for book-structured publications — it adds frontmatter (title page, preface, TOC), chapter/part/appendix structure, and backmatter (index, glossary). Use bookmap for formal printed deliverables like AMMs; ditamap for online documentation.'},
      {q:'What is a conref and how does it work?',a:'Conref (Content Reference) is DITA\'s element-level reuse mechanism. A source element with a unique id contains the content; a referencing element with conref="file.dita#topicid/elementid" is replaced by the source content at publish time. The referencing element must be the same type as the source. Use for shared warnings, notes, and repeated content blocks. Conref prevents content duplication — change the source once, update everywhere.'},
      {q:'What is a keyref and how does it differ from a conref?',a:'Keyref is DITA\'s variable substitution mechanism. Keys are defined in the map (keydef element); topics reference keys by name (keyword keyref="product-name"). At publish time, the keyref resolves to the value defined in the context map. Keyref is for variable text (product names, specifications, phone numbers) and variable links; conref is for reusing entire element content blocks. Keyref is map-contextual; conref is file-path based.'},
      {q:'Explain DITA profiling. What attributes are used?',a:'Profiling marks content with metadata attributes identifying which audience, product, or platform the content applies to. Standard profiling attributes: product, platform, audience, otherprops (legacy), props (DITA 2.0). Value: product="737-classic 737-ng". At publish time, a DITAVAL file tells the DITA-OT to include, exclude, or flag content based on these attributes. Same source, multiple customized outputs.'},
      {q:'What is a DITAVAL file?',a:'A DITAVAL file is an XML filter file specifying conditional processing actions. It contains prop elements: &lt;prop action="exclude" att="product" val="737-ng"/&gt;. Actions: include (always show), exclude (remove from output), flag (show with visual marker), passthrough. Applied to a DITA-OT transformation scenario to produce variant-specific output without modifying source files.'},
      {q:'What is the DITA Open Toolkit (DITA-OT)?',a:'The DITA-OT is the open-source publishing engine that transforms DITA XML into output formats. It processes: reads the DITA map and all referenced topics, resolves conrefs/keyrefs/conditional processing, applies XSLT transformations (with stylesheets), and produces output. Standard formats: PDF (via Apache FOP), HTML5, EPUB, XHTML. Oxygen XML Editor includes the DITA-OT and provides a GUI for configuring and running transformation scenarios.'},
      {q:'What is DITA specialization?',a:'Specialization extends base DITA types to create domain-specific element sets. The key principle is is-a: a specialized element is a specific variant of its base type, processable by any DITA tool using base type rules. Example: troubleshooting specializes task. Built-in specializations: troubleshooting (DITA 1.3), bookmap, Learning & Training, Machinery. Custom specializations require DTD/XSD changes and should only be done when base DITA cannot meet the content model needs.'},
      {q:'What does "shortdesc" do in a DITA topic?',a:'The shortdesc (short description) element serves multiple roles: appears as hover text in navigation links, as the first paragraph in published HTML, as search result previews in web portals, and as a summary in generated link previews. A well-written shortdesc (1-2 sentences) dramatically improves content findability. Best practice: every topic should have a shortdesc.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between steps and steps-unordered in a DITA task?',a:'steps uses an ordered list (numbered sequence that must be followed in order). steps-unordered renders as a bulleted list (actions that can be done in any order). Use steps for sequential procedures where order matters; use steps-unordered for configuration options or settings where the user can do them in any order.'},
      {q:'What is a DITA properties table?',a:'The properties element is a DITA-specific table construct in reference topics, designed for two- or three-column property/value/description tables. It uses prophead (header row with proptypehd/propvaluehd/propdeschd) and property elements (with proptype/propvalue/propdesc). It renders more semantically than a generic table. Use it in reference topics for specifications and parameter documentation.'},
      {q:'How do you cross-reference between DITA topics?',a:'Use the &lt;xref&gt; element. For internal cross-references: &lt;xref href="relative/path/topic.dita"&gt;Link text&lt;/xref&gt;. For element-level: &lt;xref href="topic.dita#topicid/elementid"/&gt;. For external URLs: &lt;xref href="https://..." format="html" scope="external"&gt;. Preferred approach for reusable topics: use keyref instead of href to avoid hardcoded paths: &lt;xref keyref="key-name"&gt;Link text&lt;/xref&gt;.'},
      {q:'What is a conref range?',a:'Introduced in DITA 1.2, conref range reuses a contiguous sequence of elements. Use conref on the first element and conrefend on the last: &lt;step conref="source.dita#task/step2" conrefend="source.dita#task/step5"/&gt;. This pulls steps 2 through 5 from the source task into the referencing task — useful for reusing a subset of a longer procedure.'},
      {q:'Explain DITA branch filtering (DITA 1.3).',a:'Branch filtering uses ditavalref elements within map branches to apply different DITAVAL filters per branch in a single transformation. This allows producing output for multiple product variants from one transformation run, rather than running separate transformations with separate maps. The ditavalmeta/dvrResourcePrefix element gives output files distinct names per branch to avoid collisions.'},
      {q:'What is a scoped key (DITA 1.3)?',a:'Key scopes (keyscope attribute on topicgroup or topicref) allow the same key name to resolve to different values in different parts of the same map. Essential for multi-product publications: &lt;topicgroup keyscope="product-a"&gt; can define keys="product-name" = "Product A"; &lt;topicgroup keyscope="product-b"&gt; defines the same keys="product-name" = "Product B". Both branches reference the same key name, but resolve to different values.'},
      {q:'What are relationship tables in DITA?',a:'A reltable (relationship table) in a DITA map defines link relationships between topics centrally, without embedding related-links in individual topics. Each row defines related topics; the DITA-OT generates related-link sections in output based on the table. Advantage: topics remain free of hard-coded links — all relationships managed from one place in the map. Better for reuse and easier to maintain at scale.'},
      {q:'What DITA version introduced the troubleshooting topic type?',a:'DITA 1.3 (2015) introduced the troubleshooting topic type. It specializes task and adds troublebody containing condition (what the symptom is) and troubleSolution (containing cause and remedy elements). Troubleshooting topics are used for fault isolation documentation — BITE fault codes, error codes, and diagnostic procedures in aerospace and software documentation.'},
      {q:'What is "topic-based authoring" and why does it matter?',a:'Topic-based authoring means writing content as small, self-contained, atomic topics (one concept, one procedure, one reference item) rather than as chapters in a linear book. Each topic must make sense independently. Benefits: reuse (topics appear in multiple publications), flexibility (topics assembled differently for different audiences), findability (every page is page one), and parallel authoring (multiple writers work on different topics simultaneously without conflicts).'},
      {q:'In DITA, what does processing-role="resource-only" mean?',a:'A topicref with processing-role="resource-only" tells the DITA-OT to process the referenced topic (for conref resolution and keyref) but not include it in the output table of contents or publication. Used for conref library files (warnings-library.dita, notes-library.dita) that provide reuse targets but should not appear as navigation items in the published documentation.'},
      {q:'How do you handle a note that needs to appear in 100 different task topics?',a:'Create a shared library topic (warnings-library.dita) containing the note with a unique id. Reference it via conref in all 100 task topics: &lt;note conref="shared/warnings-library.dita#warnings-lib/warning-id"/&gt;. At publish time, the DITA-OT replaces each conref with the actual note content. When the note wording must change (safety review, regulatory requirement), update the single source — all 100 topics update automatically at next publish.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between &lt;note type="warning"&gt; and &lt;note type="caution"&gt; in DITA?',a:'In DITA, note type values follow the common technical documentation convention: warning indicates potential for personal injury; caution indicates potential for equipment damage without injury risk; danger is used for imminent fatal risk (in some schemas). The semantic distinction is critical in aerospace and safety-critical documentation — a warning must appear before steps with injury risk. The rendered visual treatment (icon, color) is defined by the output stylesheet, not DITA itself.'},
      {q:'What is a glossentry topic in DITA?',a:'A glossentry topic is a DITA topic type specialized for glossary entries. It contains: glossterm (the term being defined) and glossdef (the definition). Glossentry topics are assembled into a glossary using a DITA map. The DITA-OT can generate a formatted glossary in output. Terms marked with &lt;term keyref="glossentry-key"&gt; in topics can hover-link to their definitions in HTML output.'},
      {q:'What is the prolog element in DITA?',a:'The prolog element contains metadata about a topic, appearing between the title/shortdesc and the body. Common prolog children: author (who created it), critdates (created/revised dates), metadata (containing audience, keywords, prodinfo, category), permissions (access control for CCMS). Prolog metadata is used for search indexing (keywords in HTML meta tags), CCMS workflow management, and content filtering by audience or product.'},
      {q:'Describe a DITA publishing pipeline from source to output.',a:'(1) Author writes DITA topics and maps. (2) DITA-OT reads the root map and discovers all referenced topics. (3) DITA-OT resolves conrefs (replaces references with source content), keyrefs (substitutes variable values), and conditional processing (applies DITAVAL filter to include/exclude profiled content). (4) DITA-OT applies XSLT stylesheets to transform the resolved XML into the target format. (5) For PDF: XSLT produces XSL-FO; Apache FOP renders PDF. (6) Output is written to the output directory.'},
      {q:'What is the @collection-type attribute on a topicref?',a:'collection-type on a topicref controls how child topics are related to each other and to the parent. Values: unordered (default — children are related, no specific sequence), sequence (previous/next links generated between child topics), choice (one of several alternatives), family (every topic links to every other). sequence is commonly used for task sequences where the user must read topics in order.'},
      {q:'How does the DITA-OT handle conrefs at publish time?',a:'The DITA-OT has a "preprocess" phase that runs before format-specific transformation. During preprocessing, it: (1) resolves conrefs by finding the source element at the conref address and substituting its content in place of the referencing element; (2) resolves keyrefs against the key space defined by the root map; (3) applies DITAVAL filter rules (including/excluding profiled elements); (4) normalizes the resulting content. The XSLT transformation then runs on this resolved content.'},
      {q:'What is DITA 2.0 and what major changes did it introduce?',a:'DITA 2.0 (2023) is a significant cleanup and modernization. Major changes: removed deprecated elements (topichead without href, navref, anchor — replaced with better mechanisms); simplified some element models; improved multimedia support (audio, video natively); removed the Learning & Training specialization (moved to separate document); clarified map processing rules; and introduced props as the consolidated general-purpose profiling attribute. DITA 1.3 remains the most widely deployed version in production.'},
      {q:'What is a keydef without an href?',a:'A keydef without href is a "text variable" key. It defines a key that resolves to text content (from keyword in topicmeta) rather than to a file link. The keyword\'s text is substituted wherever &lt;keyword keyref="key-name"/&gt; appears. Use for product names, version numbers, phone numbers, or any text that varies by publication. With href, keydef defines a target resource (topic or URL) for link keyrefs.'},
      {q:'Explain how DITA supports localization/translation.',a:'DITA supports localization through: (1) Single topic per file — each file is sent to a translation agency independently. (2) Conrefs translate the source element once; all references update automatically from the translated source. (3) Keyrefs allow product-specific text (brand names, phone numbers) to be defined per language in the map — not embedded in topics. (4) @xml:lang attribute marks content language. (5) DITA-OT supports translated input for multi-language publishing from the same map.'},
      {q:'What is a DITA learning map (learningMap) and when is it used?',a:'learningMap is a DITA specialization from the Learning & Training specification. It assembles learning content (learningContent, learningOverview, learningSummary, learningAssessment topics) into a structured course or module. Used for SCORM-compatible e-learning content and training material. The specialization enforces pedagogical structure: overview → content → assessment. Common in corporate training, military training documentation, and regulated-industry qualification training.'},
      {q:'What does the @chunk attribute do on a topicref?',a:'The chunk attribute controls how the DITA-OT handles topic file aggregation in output. chunk="to-content" combines the parent topic and all child topics into a single output file (single HTML page or PDF section). chunk="to-navigation" keeps the hierarchy for navigation but produces separate output files for each topic. Common use: a top-level topicref for a chapter with chunk="to-content" produces a single chapter HTML file instead of separate files per topic.'},
    ]
  },
  xml: {
    label:'XML',
    icon:'🔧',
    questions:[
      {q:'What does XML stand for?',a:'Extensible Markup Language. It is a meta-language for defining custom markup languages. XML defines rules for encoding documents in a format that is both human-readable and machine-readable. "Extensible" means you define your own elements and attributes — unlike HTML which has a fixed tag set.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between well-formed and valid XML?',a:'Well-formed XML satisfies XML syntax rules: has a single root element, all elements are properly closed, elements are properly nested, attribute values are quoted, special characters are escaped. Valid XML is additionally valid against a schema (DTD, XSD, or RelaxNG) — meaning elements and attributes follow the rules defined in that schema (required elements present, correct order, correct data types). DITA files must be both well-formed AND valid against the DITA DTD.'},
      {q:'What is a DOCTYPE declaration and what does it do?',a:'The DOCTYPE declaration (Document Type Declaration) specifies which DTD the XML document follows. Example: &lt;!DOCTYPE task PUBLIC "-//OASIS//DTD DITA Task//EN" "task.dtd"&gt;. It tells the parser/validator where to find the schema rules (the DTD file) for validating this document. For DITA, the DOCTYPE identifies the topic type (task, concept, reference) and the DTD location.'},
      {q:'What is an XML namespace?',a:'A namespace is a mechanism for qualifying XML element and attribute names to prevent conflicts when combining XML from different vocabularies. Declared with xmlns: &lt;dita xmlns:ditaarch="http://dita.oasis-open.org/architecture/2005/"&gt;. The namespace URI is a unique identifier (not necessarily a real URL). In DITA, namespaces are used for the specialization architecture (@class and @domains attributes). Most DITA authors rarely declare namespaces manually.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between an attribute and an element in XML?',a:'An element is a markup unit that can contain content (text, other elements, or mixed): &lt;title&gt;My Topic&lt;/title&gt;. An attribute is a name-value pair on an opening tag providing metadata about the element: &lt;topic id="my-id" product="737"&gt;. Rules of thumb: use elements for content that users see; use attributes for metadata about elements. In DITA, most content is in elements; profiling conditions, ids, and references are in attributes.'},
      {q:'What are CDATA sections in XML?',a:'CDATA (Character Data) sections mark content that should not be parsed as XML. Used to include literal characters like &lt;, &gt;, and & without escaping: &lt;![CDATA[5 &lt; 10 &amp;&amp; a &gt; 0]]&gt;. In DITA practice, CDATA sections are rare — you typically escape special characters using &amp;lt; &amp;gt; &amp;amp; rather than CDATA. CDATA sections are common in SVG content embedded in XML.'},
      {q:'What is XPath?',a:'XPath (XML Path Language) is a query language for selecting nodes in an XML document. It uses path expressions like /topic/title or //note[@type=\'warning\']. XPath is used in XSLT (to select elements to transform), in Schematron rules, in Oxygen\'s XPath query tool, and in DITA-OT customization. Basic XPath: / selects root; // selects anywhere; [] is a predicate (filter); @ selects attributes; text() selects text content.'},
      {q:'What is XSLT?',a:'XSL Transformations — an XML-based language for transforming XML documents into other formats. The DITA-OT uses XSLT to transform DITA XML into HTML5, XHTML, PDF (via XSL-FO), and other formats. An XSLT stylesheet contains templates that match specific XML elements and define how to render them. DITA-OT customization typically involves writing XSLT overrides that add to or replace the default transformation behavior.'},
      {q:'What is a DTD?',a:'Document Type Definition — a schema format for defining valid XML structure. A DTD specifies: element declarations (what elements exist, their content model), attribute declarations (what attributes each element can have, their types and defaults), and entity declarations (&amp;nbsp; etc.). DITA 1.x uses DTDs. Limitations: DTDs use SGML syntax (not XML), cannot express datatype constraints (all values are text). Modern alternative: XML Schema (XSD) or RelaxNG.'},
      {q:'What is XSD?',a:'XML Schema Definition — a more powerful XML-based alternative to DTD. XSD validates XML structure and data types (string, integer, date, etc.), allows namespace-aware validation, supports complex type inheritance, and uses XML syntax (so it\'s parseable as XML). DITA 1.3 provides both DTD and XSD versions. Oxygen can validate DITA against either. For custom applications processing DITA, XSD validation in Java is more practical than DTD validation.'},
      {q:'What is the @class attribute in DITA?',a:'The DITA @class attribute is the backbone of the specialization mechanism. Every DITA element has a class attribute that traces its inheritance: class="- topic/p task/p -". This tells processors: this element is a p in the task module, which is a p in the topic module. DITA-OT uses class attributes to apply transformations to specialized elements using base-type rules — this is how backward compatibility is maintained without the tool knowing about every specialization.'},
      {q:'What is RelaxNG?',a:'RelaxNG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) is an XML schema language that is simpler than XSD but equally powerful. DITA 2.0 switched from DTDs to RelaxNG as the primary schema format. RelaxNG uses a compact syntax (.rnc) or XML syntax (.rng). Oxygen supports RelaxNG validation. RelaxNG is easier to read and write than XSD and more expressive than DTD.'},
      {q:'What does "encoding" mean in an XML declaration?',a:'The XML declaration (<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>) specifies the character encoding of the file. UTF-8 is the standard for DITA files and supports all Unicode characters — essential for multilingual documentation. If omitted, UTF-8 or UTF-16 is assumed. Specify encoding="UTF-8" explicitly to avoid ambiguity. Wrong encoding causes character corruption in published output, especially for non-Latin characters (Arabic, Chinese, Hindi, Japanese).'},
      {q:'What is XML entity? Name three predefined XML entities.',a:'An XML entity is a name that represents a string of text or a character. Predefined entities replace characters that have special meaning in XML: &amp;lt; = < (less-than); &amp;gt; = > (greater-than); &amp;amp; = & (ampersand); &amp;apos; = \' (apostrophe); &amp;quot; = " (quotation mark). In DITA, you use these when your content must contain these characters literally (e.g., a code sample with &lt; or a note with & in a measurement).'},
      {q:'What is the XML Infoset?',a:'The XML Information Set (Infoset) is the abstract data model of a parsed XML document — the set of information items (elements, attributes, text, comments, processing instructions, namespaces) and their properties. The Infoset is what XPath and XSLT operate on. Understanding the Infoset helps explain why serialization (the text of the XML file) and the processed document model can differ — e.g., whitespace handling differences between parsers.'},
      {q:'What is XInclude and how does it differ from a DITA conref?',a:'XInclude is an XML mechanism for including content from external files at parse time: &lt;xi:include href="file.xml"/&gt;. The referenced XML is physically inserted at that location before processing. DITA conref is a reference resolved during DITA-OT preprocessing — the source and referencing elements remain separate files. Key difference: XInclude is a general XML mechanism (not DITA-aware); conref is DITA-specific and maintains DITA element-type matching rules.'},
      {q:'What is SAX vs. DOM parsing?',a:'SAX (Simple API for XML) is an event-driven parser: it reads the XML sequentially and fires events (startElement, endElement, characters) as it encounters each part. Memory efficient; good for large files; cannot navigate backward. DOM (Document Object Model) parses the entire document into a tree in memory: slower and memory-intensive but allows random access to any part of the document. DITA-OT uses DOM-like processing (Saxon XSLT processor) because XSLT requires full document access.'},
      {q:'What is an XML processing instruction?',a:'A processing instruction (PI) provides instructions to XML processors (not content). Syntax: &lt;?target content?&gt;. The XML declaration &lt;?xml version="1.0"?&gt; is technically not a PI but looks similar. Real PIs: &lt;?xml-stylesheet href="style.css" type="text/css"?&gt; or &lt;?Pub Caret?&gt; (Arbortext editor bookmark). DITA processing instructions are rare in standard authoring but appear in some CCMS implementations.'},
      {q:'What is namespace-aware parsing?',a:'A namespace-aware XML parser distinguishes element names by their namespace URI, not just their local name. So &lt;p xmlns="http://www.dita.oasis-open.org/"&gt; and &lt;p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"&gt; are different elements despite having the same local name "p". DITA-OT processing is namespace-aware. When writing XSLT for DITA customization, you must handle DITA\'s namespace declarations correctly to match elements.'},
      {q:'What is XML Schema (XSD) "simple type" vs. "complex type"?',a:'A simple type defines the value constraints for an attribute or text-only element: &lt;xs:simpleType&gt; with restriction, list, or union facets (e.g., xs:integer, xs:date, xs:string pattern). A complex type defines an element that has child elements and/or attributes: &lt;xs:complexType&gt; with xs:sequence, xs:choice, or xs:all model groups. Most DITA elements are complex types; attribute values are validated as simple types.'},
      {q:'What is the role of XSLT templates in DITA publishing?',a:'XSLT templates match specific XML elements and define how they are transformed. The match attribute uses XPath: &lt;xsl:template match="//task"&gt; matches all task elements. The template body defines the output: HTML, XSL-FO, or other XML. DITA-OT customization uses xsl:import to load the default DITA-OT stylesheets, then override specific templates: &lt;xsl:template match="note[@type=\'warning\']"&gt; to customize warning rendering. Priority resolution determines which template fires when multiple match.'},
      {q:'What does "well-formed" XML mean?',a:'Well-formed XML must: have exactly one root element; have all elements properly closed (either </tag> or <tag/>); properly nest elements (no overlapping); quote all attribute values; escape special characters (&lt; &gt; &amp; in content; &quot; &apos; in attributes); have an XML declaration or valid inferred encoding; have valid names (start with letter or underscore, no spaces). A well-formed XML file can be parsed without a schema; validity (against a schema) is an additional check.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between &lt;element/&gt; and &lt;element&gt;&lt;/element&gt;?',a:'Both represent empty elements. &lt;element/&gt; is the self-closing empty element tag (XML shorthand). &lt;element&gt;&lt;/element&gt; is the start tag followed by empty end tag. They are semantically identical in XML. In DITA, empty conref elements use the self-closing form: &lt;note conref="lib.dita#lib/warning"/&gt;. Note: HTML5 does not support self-closing syntax for non-void elements — this is an XML-specific feature.'},
      {q:'What is Schematron and when is it used in DITA?',a:'Schematron is a rule-based validation language for XML, used to enforce business rules that DTD and XSD cannot express. Example: "Every task topic must have a shortdesc" or "A warning note must precede any step that involves electrical hazards." DITA teams with strict style guide requirements use Schematron rules (often embedded in the DITA DTD or run as separate validation) to catch authoring errors that XML validation misses. Oxygen XML Editor supports Schematron validation.'},
      {q:'What is "mixed content" in XML?',a:'Mixed content is an element that can contain both text and child elements: &lt;p&gt;This is &lt;b&gt;bold&lt;/b&gt; text.&lt;/p&gt;. The DITA paragraph (&lt;p&gt;) allows mixed content. In contrast, element-only content (like &lt;taskbody&gt;) can only contain elements (no direct text). DTD declaration: &lt;!ELEMENT p (#PCDATA | ph | term | ...)*&gt; defines mixed content. Pure text elements: &lt;!ELEMENT keyword (#PCDATA)&gt;. Mixed content elements can be tricky for XSLT transforms because text nodes and element nodes must both be handled.'},
      {q:'What is the XPath difference between // and /?',a:'/ is the absolute path separator (starting from root or separating parent from child). //topic selects topic elements anywhere in the document (descendant-or-self axis). /topic selects only root-level topic. //*/note selects all note descendants of all elements. Practical: //note[@type="warning"] finds all warning notes anywhere in the document. /map/topicref finds topicrefs that are direct children of map. // is powerful but can be slow on large documents; use specific paths where performance matters.'},
      {q:'What is an XML character reference?',a:'A character reference represents a Unicode character by its code point. Decimal: &amp;#169; = © (copyright). Hexadecimal: &amp;#xA9; = © (same character, hex notation). Used when the character is not easily typeable or when the character has special XML meaning. In DITA: &amp;#8212; = — (em dash), &amp;#169; = ©, &amp;#174; = ®. Note: XML entities (&amp;amp; etc.) are named; character references (&amp;#N;) are numeric.'},
      {q:'What is a namespace prefix in XML?',a:'A namespace prefix is a short alias for a namespace URI. Declare: xmlns:ditaarch="http://dita.oasis-open.org/architecture/2005/". Use: ditaarch:DITAArchVersion="1.3". The prefix must be declared before use (either on the element itself or an ancestor). Default namespace (xmlns=) applies to unprefixed elements. In XSLT for DITA customization, you declare namespace prefixes to reference DITA elements that carry namespaces. Multiple prefixes can map to the same URI.'},
      {q:'What is "canonical XML"?',a:'Canonical XML is a standardized form of an XML document, produced by a canonicalization algorithm (C14N). It: converts all encoding to UTF-8, expands entity references, removes the XML declaration, normalizes line endings to LF, sorts namespace declarations and attributes, adds namespace declarations on every element. Used for XML digital signatures (XML-DSIG) — canonicalization ensures the signed content is deterministic regardless of original serialization differences. In DITA, relevant for regulated document signing and integrity verification.'},
    ]
  },
  git: {
    label:'Git',
    icon:'🌿',
    questions:[
      {q:'What is the difference between git pull and git fetch?',a:'git fetch downloads new commits from the remote into your local repository but does NOT merge them into your working branch. After fetch, you can review the changes (git log origin/main) before integrating. git pull = git fetch + git merge: downloads AND merges immediately. git fetch is safer for reviewing changes first; git pull is faster for trusted upstream branches. git pull --rebase applies your local commits on top of the fetched commits instead of merging.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between git merge and git rebase?',a:'git merge combines two branches by creating a merge commit, preserving full history including when the branch diverged. git rebase replays your commits on top of the target branch — creates a linear history as if you started from the latest commit. Merge: safer for shared/public branches (never rebase public history); preserves truth about when branches diverged. Rebase: cleaner linear history for feature branches before merging; rewrites commit hashes (do not rebase public branches).'},
      {q:'What does git stash do?',a:'git stash temporarily saves your uncommitted changes (both staged and unstaged) to a stack and reverts your working directory to the last commit. This lets you switch branches or pull changes without committing incomplete work. git stash pop restores the stashed changes and removes them from the stash. git stash list shows all stashes. git stash apply stash@{0} applies a specific stash without removing it. Useful when you need to urgently switch context without committing work-in-progress.'},
      {q:'Explain the git workflow for a feature branch.',a:'(1) git checkout main && git pull (start from latest). (2) git checkout -b feature/my-feature (create branch). (3) Make changes, git add, git commit repeatedly. (4) git push origin feature/my-feature (push branch). (5) Open a pull request on GitHub for review. (6) Address review comments, push more commits. (7) PR approved: merge into main (via GitHub UI or git merge). (8) git checkout main && git pull (update local). (9) git branch -d feature/my-feature (clean up).'},
      {q:'What is git cherry-pick?',a:'git cherry-pick applies a specific commit from one branch to another, without merging the entire branch. Usage: git cherry-pick abc1234 (apply commit abc1234 to current branch). Useful when a bug fix on one branch needs to be applied to another release branch without merging all changes. Creates a new commit with the same changes but a different hash. For documentation: if a critical safety correction is committed to a feature branch, cherry-pick it to main immediately without waiting for the full feature.'},
      {q:'What is git blame?',a:'git blame shows the last commit that modified each line of a file, with author and date: git blame filename.dita. Output format: commit-hash (Author Date Line-number) Content. Use it to find who made a specific change and when, then use git show commit-hash to see the full context of that commit. In documentation: when a procedure step is suspect, git blame identifies who added it and the associated commit message (ideally linking to an SME review or issue number).'},
      {q:'What is the .gitignore file?',a:'A text file listing patterns for files and directories that Git should not track. Patterns: *.pdf (all PDF files), /out/ (output directory), .DS_Store (macOS metadata files), *.lock (lock files). Place in repository root; affects all subdirectories unless overridden. git check-ignore -v filename tests whether a file is ignored and why. For DITA: ignore /out/, /output/, all DITA-OT generated files. Generated output must never be committed — it bloats the repo and creates meaningless diff noise.'},
      {q:'What is git log --oneline and how do you use it?',a:'git log --oneline shows a compact one-line commit history: short hash + commit message. Useful switches: --oneline --graph (ASCII branch visualization), -10 (last 10 commits only), --author="Sanhita" (filter by author), --since="2024-01-01" (commits after date), --grep="ATA-29" (search commit messages), -- topics/ (commits affecting specific path). Use git log to audit what changed, find when a change was introduced, or trace a regression.'},
      {q:'What does HEAD mean in Git?',a:'HEAD is a pointer to the current position in the repository — usually the tip of the current branch (most recent commit). HEAD~1 = one commit before HEAD (parent). HEAD~2 = two commits before. HEAD^2 = second parent (for merge commits). Detached HEAD means HEAD points directly to a commit hash (not a branch tip) — this happens when you checkout a specific commit or tag. In detached HEAD state, commits are "floating" and can be lost if not branched.'},
      {q:'What is a fast-forward merge?',a:'A fast-forward merge occurs when the target branch has not diverged from the source — the source branch is simply ahead. Git can advance the target branch pointer to the source branch tip without creating a merge commit. Result: clean linear history. If no divergence has occurred (main hasn\'t changed since you branched), git merge feature/x performs a fast-forward. Use git merge --no-ff to force a merge commit even when fast-forward is possible (for clearer branch history tracking).'},
      {q:'Explain the three areas in Git\'s data model.',a:'(1) Working directory: the actual files on disk. You edit files here. Status: "modified" if changed since last commit. (2) Staging area (index): where you prepare the next commit. git add moves changes here. Only staged changes go into the next commit. (3) Repository (.git directory): the committed history database. git commit saves staged changes as a new commit. This three-area model enables committing specific changes while keeping other modifications in progress in the working directory.'},
      {q:'What is git tag and why use it?',a:'A tag is a permanent label for a specific commit — typically used for releases or documentation revisions. Lightweight tag: git tag v2.1 (pointer to commit, no metadata). Annotated tag: git tag -a v2.1 -m "Release 2.1: ATA-29 hydraulic chapter revised" (stores tagger name, date, message). git push origin --tags pushes tags to GitHub. Tags are not pushed by default with git push. Use annotated tags for releases — the metadata provides audit trail for formal document releases.'},
      {q:'What is git reset and what are its three modes?',a:'git reset moves HEAD (and optionally the working directory and index) to a specified commit. Three modes: --soft: moves HEAD to commit; keeps staged changes and working directory changes intact (safe). --mixed (default): moves HEAD; unstages staged changes but keeps working directory (moderately safe). --hard: moves HEAD; discards all staged and working directory changes (DESTRUCTIVE — changes are lost). Never git reset --hard on pushed commits — this rewrites history that others may have pulled.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between origin and upstream in Git?',a:'origin is the default name for the remote repository you cloned from (your fork or the main repo). upstream is the conventional name for the original repository when you have forked it. Workflow: you fork repo A → clone your fork (origin). Add the original as upstream: git remote add upstream https://github.com/original/repo.git. Then: git fetch upstream pulls changes from the original; git fetch origin pulls from your fork. Use upstream to stay current with the original project.'},
      {q:'What is git reflog?',a:'git reflog records every position HEAD has been at, including commits, checkouts, resets, and rebases — even those that are no longer reachable from any branch. It is your safety net: if you accidentally deleted commits with git reset --hard or rebased incorrectly, git reflog shows the previous HEAD positions and you can recover: git checkout -b recovery-branch abc1234 (where abc1234 is the lost commit hash from reflog). Reflog is local and expires after ~90 days.'},
      {q:'What is git bisect?',a:'git bisect is a binary search tool for finding the commit that introduced a bug (or documentation error). Usage: git bisect start → git bisect bad (current state is bad) → git bisect good v2.0 (version 2.0 was good). Git checks out the midpoint commit; you test it. git bisect good or git bisect bad guides the binary search. Git finds the exact commit that introduced the problem in O(log n) steps. For documentation: find exactly which commit introduced an incorrect procedure.'},
      {q:'What is a pre-commit hook?',a:'A Git hook is a script that runs automatically at specific Git events. The pre-commit hook runs before every commit. Use it to: run markdownlint on Markdown files and abort commit if errors exist; run xmllint to validate DITA files; check for TODO or FIXME markers; enforce commit message format. Hooks are stored in .git/hooks/; not committed to the repository. Use tools like husky (for Node.js projects) or pre-commit (Python) to manage hooks across a team via a committed configuration file.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between git rm and just deleting a file?',a:'Deleting a file manually removes it from the working directory but leaves it in Git\'s index (still tracked). git status shows it as "deleted" unstaged. You still need git add (or git rm) to stage the deletion for the next commit. git rm removes the file from both the working directory AND the index in one step — the deletion is immediately staged. git rm --cached removes the file from tracking only (keeps it on disk, adds to .gitignore).'},
      {q:'What is the difference between git clone --depth=1 and a full clone?',a:'A full clone downloads the complete repository history — all commits from all time. A shallow clone (--depth=1) downloads only the most recent commit — no history. Advantage: much faster and uses less disk space. Disadvantage: git blame, git log, and git bisect don\'t work fully (no history). Useful for CI/CD pipelines that just need the source to build, or for very large repositories where full history is impractical. You can unshallow later: git fetch --unshallow.'},
      {q:'What does git remote -v show?',a:'git remote -v lists all configured remotes with their fetch and push URLs. Example output: "origin  https://github.com/username/repo.git (fetch)"; "origin  https://github.com/username/repo.git (push)". Useful for: confirming which remote repository you\'re connected to, verifying you have both upstream and origin configured, and checking SSH vs. HTTPS URL. Use git remote set-url origin new-url to update a remote URL (e.g., switching from HTTPS to SSH).'},
      {q:'What is a bare Git repository?',a:'A bare repository contains only the Git repository data (the .git directory contents) without a working directory. Created with git init --bare. Used as a shared remote repository (like what GitHub hosts). You cannot edit files directly in a bare repository. When you run git clone, you get a normal repository with a working directory that tracks the bare repository as origin. Bare repositories are the standard format for Git servers.'},
      {q:'Explain the difference between git checkout and git switch.',a:'git checkout is the older, overloaded command that handles: switching branches (git checkout branch-name), creating branches (git checkout -b new-branch), restoring files (git checkout -- filename), checking out specific commits. git switch (introduced in Git 2.23) is a focused command for branch operations only: git switch branch-name (switch), git switch -c new-branch (create + switch). git restore (also 2.23) handles file restoration. The split makes the interface clearer; git checkout still works for backward compatibility.'},
      {q:'What is a GitHub fork vs. a clone?',a:'A fork is a GitHub-level copy of a repository under your GitHub account — you own the fork, can push to it, and can open pull requests from it back to the original. A clone is a local copy of a repository on your machine. Typical open-source contribution workflow: fork the repo on GitHub → clone YOUR fork locally → work on changes → push to your fork → open a PR from your fork to the original. Without forking, you cannot push to repositories where you don\'t have write access.'},
      {q:'What is git worktree?',a:'git worktree allows multiple working directories for the same repository simultaneously. Usage: git worktree add ../hotfix-branch hotfix/urgent-fix. Now you can work in the main working directory AND the hotfix directory simultaneously, each on its own branch. This is useful when you need to fix a critical bug in production while also working on a feature branch — no need to stash, commit work-in-progress, or clone the entire repository again.'},
      {q:'What is the GitHub Actions "on: push: paths" filter?',a:'The paths filter in a GitHub Actions workflow limits when the workflow runs based on which files changed. Example: on: push: paths: [\'**.dita\', \'**.ditamap\']. The workflow only runs when DITA files change, not when README.md or .github/ files change. This reduces unnecessary CI runs, saves compute minutes, and speeds up the feedback loop. For documentation CI: run DITA-OT builds only when DITA source files change; run markdownlint only when .md files change.'},
    ]
  },
  markdown: {
    label:'Markdown',
    icon:'📝',
    questions:[
      {q:'What is the correct Markdown syntax for a third-level heading?',a:'### Heading Text — three hash signs (octothorpes) followed by a space and the heading text. # = H1 (document title, only one per page), ## = H2, ### = H3, #### = H4. Headings must be preceded by a blank line (per markdownlint rule MD022). Starting with ## or ### without a preceding # violates markdownlint MD041 (first heading should be H1).'},
      {q:'What is GitHub Flavored Markdown (GFM) and how does it extend CommonMark?',a:'GFM is GitHub\'s Markdown dialect, based on the CommonMark specification with extensions. GFM adds: tables (using | pipe syntax with --- separator row), task lists (- [x] done / - [ ] incomplete), strikethrough (~~text~~), fenced code blocks with language identifiers for syntax highlighting, autolinks (bare URLs are clickable), and disallowed raw HTML filtering. GFM is the default on GitHub, GitLab, and most developer documentation platforms.'},
      {q:'How do you create a table in Markdown?',a:'Use the pipe | and hyphen - syntax: column headers on first row, --- separator row (with optional alignment colons), then data rows. Example:\n| Name | Type | Required |\n|:-----|:----:|--------:|\n| id   | string | Yes    |\nColon positions: :--- = left, :---: = center, ---: = right. The separator row must have at least three hyphens per cell. Tables are a GFM extension (not in original Markdown).'},
      {q:'What is YAML front matter in Markdown and what is it used for?',a:'YAML front matter is a block of YAML metadata at the top of a Markdown file between triple dashes (---). It stores structured metadata that documentation frameworks read to configure the page: title, description, date, author, tags, sidebar_position, draft status, slug. Frameworks like Docusaurus, MkDocs, Hugo, and Jekyll process this metadata to generate navigation, SEO meta tags, categories, and site structure. It is the Markdown equivalent of DITA\'s prolog metadata.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between CommonMark and standard Markdown?',a:'Original Markdown (John Gruber, 2004) was ambiguous in many edge cases — different parsers rendered the same Markdown differently. CommonMark (2014) is a strict, unambiguous specification of Markdown with a comprehensive test suite and formal grammar. CommonMark standardizes behavior for: nested lists indentation, emphasis (bold/italic) parsing rules, link and image syntax, and raw HTML handling. Most modern Markdown parsers (GitHub, GitLab, Pandoc, VS Code) implement CommonMark as their base.'},
      {q:'What is the Markdown syntax for an inline code span?',a:'Backtick(s) around the code: \`code here\`. For code containing a backtick: use double backticks with spaces: \`\` code with \` backtick \`\`. Multiple backtick levels allow nesting: \`\`\` for content with double backticks. Inline code renders in a monospace font. In DITA, the equivalent is &lt;codeph&gt; (code phrase). Use inline code for: command names, file names, function names, element names, and short code snippets in running text.'},
      {q:'How do you create a fenced code block with syntax highlighting in Markdown?',a:'Use triple backticks followed by the language identifier: ```python ... ``` or triple tildes: ~~~xml ... ~~~. The language identifier triggers syntax highlighting in capable renderers (GitHub, VS Code, documentation sites). Common language identifiers: python, javascript, xml, json, bash, yaml, sql, java, html, css. For DITA XML: ```xml. For shell commands: ```bash or ```shell. The language identifier is optional — omit for plain monospace without highlighting.'},
      {q:'What is the markdownlint rule MD001 and what does it enforce?',a:'MD001 (Heading increment) requires that heading levels only increment by one. You cannot jump from H1 (#) directly to H3 (###) — you must have H2 (##) in between. This prevents incorrect heading hierarchy that would break document structure and accessibility (screen readers use heading hierarchy for navigation). Fix: add the missing intermediate heading level, or restructure content to use correct hierarchy.'},
      {q:'What is a reference-style link in Markdown?',a:'A reference-style link separates the link text and URL into two parts, improving readability for long URLs: [Link text][label] in the text, then [label]: https://url.com "optional title" elsewhere (usually at the bottom of the file). Example: [OASIS DITA][dita-spec]... [dita-spec]: https://www.oasis-open.org/standards/dita/. Advantage: text reads cleanly without embedded URLs; multiple links to the same URL share one definition.'},
      {q:'How do you add emphasis in Markdown? What is the difference between * and **?',a:'Single asterisk or underscore = italic (*italic* or _italic_). Double asterisk or double underscore = bold (**bold** or __bold__). Triple = bold italic (***bold italic***). Tilde (GFM only) = ~~strikethrough~~. Best practice: use * not _ for emphasis (underscores can be ambiguous inside words in some parsers). In technical writing: use bold sparingly for truly critical information (warnings, key terms on first use); italic for titles and technical terms.'},
      {q:'What is the docs-as-code approach and how does Markdown fit into it?',a:'Docs-as-code treats documentation like software source code: stored in Git version control, authored in lightweight markup (Markdown or DITA XML), reviewed via pull requests, tested with linting tools, and deployed via CI/CD pipelines. Markdown fits naturally: .md files are plain text, excellent for Git version control (diffs show meaningful content changes), writable in any text editor, and parseable by documentation frameworks (Docusaurus, MkDocs, Hugo) that produce production documentation sites.'},
      {q:'What is Pandoc and what role does it play in documentation?',a:'Pandoc is a universal document converter that transforms content between dozens of formats. Relevant for documentation: Markdown → DITA XML, Markdown → DOCX, Markdown → PDF, Markdown → EPUB, DITA → Markdown, RST → Markdown, LaTeX → Markdown. Not perfect for complex structured content, but useful for migration projects, content format standardization, and quick format conversions. Pandoc supports extensions and custom Lua filters for sophisticated transformations.'},
      {q:'What is MkDocs Material and what makes it popular for documentation?',a:'MkDocs Material is a theme for the MkDocs static site generator (Python). It is the most popular documentation theme because: it implements Google\'s Material Design; includes a powerful built-in search; supports custom navigation, versioning, social cards, dark mode, and annotations; provides excellent code block features (line highlighting, copy button, line numbers); and can be configured entirely through mkdocs.yml without custom CSS. Many major open-source projects use MkDocs Material.'},
      {q:'How do you add a note/admonition in Markdown for MkDocs Material?',a:'MkDocs Material uses a custom syntax for admonitions (callout boxes): !!! note "Optional Title"\n    Content indented with 4 spaces. Available types: note, tip, info, success, question, warning, failure, danger, bug, example, quote. For collapsible: ??? instead of !!!. This is a MkDocs-specific extension. In standard Markdown, you approximate with blockquotes (> ⚠️ **Warning:** text) or HTML &lt;div class="warning"&gt; tags.'},
      {q:'What is a Mermaid diagram and how does it work in Markdown?',a:'Mermaid is a JavaScript-based diagramming tool that renders diagrams from text descriptions in Markdown code blocks labeled "mermaid". Types: flowchart, sequenceDiagram, gitGraph, classDiagram, gantt, stateDiagram, erDiagram. GitHub renders Mermaid diagrams natively in Markdown files. MkDocs Material supports Mermaid with a plugin. Example: ```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n  A[Start] --> B[Process] --> C[End]\n```. Diagrams are version-controllable text, unlike image files.'},
      {q:'What is the correct Markdown syntax for an image with alt text?',a:'![Alt text](image-path.png) or ![Alt text](image-path.png "Optional hover title"). Alt text is required for accessibility — screen readers announce it; it displays when the image cannot load. For external images: ![Alt text](https://example.com/image.png). Reference style: ![Alt text][img-ref] then [img-ref]: path.png "title". In technical documentation, every image must have descriptive alt text. In DITA: &lt;image href="path.png"&gt;&lt;alt&gt;Alt text&lt;/alt&gt;&lt;/image&gt;.'},
      {q:'What is the Markdown syntax for a task list (checklist)?',a:'GFM task list: - [ ] Incomplete task and - [x] Complete task. Works in GitHub issues, pull requests, and Markdown files rendered by GitHub/GitLab. In GitHub issues, task list items are interactive — users can click to check/uncheck. The checkbox rendering is GitHub-specific; in standard Markdown renderers it may show as literal text. Task lists are useful for tracking documentation review checklists, publication checklists, and project milestones.'},
      {q:'How do you escape special characters in Markdown?',a:'Prefix the special character with a backslash: \\* for literal asterisk, \\_ for underscore, \\# for hash, \\[ for bracket, \\` for backtick, \\| for pipe. In code spans and code blocks, all characters are literal (no escaping needed). HTML entities also work: &amp;lt; = <, &amp;amp; = &. When you need to show Markdown syntax as text (e.g., in documentation about Markdown), use code formatting or escape the control characters.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between ATX and Setext-style headings?',a:'ATX headings use # symbols: # H1, ## H2, ### H3. Setext headings use underline characters: H1 followed by ===, H2 followed by ---. ATX style supports H1-H6; Setext only supports H1 and H2. ATX is universally preferred in modern Markdown: more compact, consistent, supports all 6 levels, and less ambiguous (a line of --- after a paragraph could be mistaken for a thematic break). markdownlint enforces consistent heading style.'},
      {q:'What markdownlint rule prevents multiple H1 headings in a document?',a:'MD025 (Multiple top-level headings in the same document) flags any file with more than one H1 heading (#). Each document should have exactly one H1 as the document title. Multiple H1 headings break document hierarchy, confuse heading navigation, and are flagged by screen readers as incorrect structure. Fix: promote or demote the extra H1 headings to the correct level (H2 or below) within the document hierarchy.'},
      {q:'What is the Markdown syntax for a blockquote?',a:'> at the start of the line followed by the quoted text: > This is a blockquote. Nesting: >> for nested blockquotes. Blockquotes can contain other Markdown: > **Note:** Blockquotes render with visual indentation and (usually) a left border. In technical documentation: use for safety notes (with emoji), regulatory quotations, and important callouts in Markdown systems that don\'t support native admonition syntax.'},
      {q:'How do you link to a heading within the same Markdown document?',a:'Use the heading text converted to a link anchor: spaces become hyphens, uppercase becomes lowercase, punctuation is removed. Example: heading "DITA Best Practices" becomes #dita-best-practices. Link: [See DITA Best Practices](#dita-best-practices). GitHub generates these anchors automatically for all headings. For headings with special characters, GitHub\'s exact algorithm may differ — test by hovering the heading link on GitHub.'},
    ]
  },
  techwriting: {
    label:'Tech Writing',
    icon:'✍️',
    questions:[
      {q:'What is the difference between a user guide and a reference manual?',a:'A user guide is task-oriented: it teaches users how to accomplish goals through explanations and procedures. It assumes users will read sections in sequence and guides them from start to finish on accomplishing tasks. A reference manual is look-up oriented: users query it for specific information (specifications, parameters, commands, error codes) without reading sequentially. Users consult reference manuals when they already know what they\'re looking for. Both map to DITA topic types: user guide = concept + task topics; reference manual = reference topics.'},
      {q:'What is controlled language and why is it important in aerospace?',a:'Controlled language restricts vocabulary and grammar to improve clarity and reduce translation costs. ASD-STE100 Simplified Technical English is the aerospace standard: approved word list (one word = one meaning), maximum sentence length (20 words for procedures, 25 for descriptive), active voice, simple tenses, one instruction per step. Importance: maintenance technicians worldwide may be non-native English speakers; clear, simple language prevents misunderstanding and reduces accident risk. Also reduces translation costs (higher TM reuse rates, fewer translator queries).'},
      {q:'Explain the concept of "Every Page is Page One" and how DITA supports it.',a:'Mark Baker\'s EPPO concept: in online documentation, readers frequently arrive at any topic from a search engine or link, not from the beginning. They haven\'t read preceding sections. Therefore, every topic must be self-contained enough to be useful without prior context — it must orient the reader, provide necessary background, and link to related content. DITA\'s topic-based authoring enforces this structurally: each topic is a separate file, must not reference "as described above," and should provide a meaningful shortdesc for search previews.'},
      {q:'What is information architecture and what are its three questions?',a:'Information architecture (IA) is the practice of organizing, structuring, and labeling content for findability. The three IA questions every user is implicitly asking: (1) Where am I? (answered by breadcrumbs, section headers, navigation context), (2) What\'s here? (answered by clear headings, titles, and topic descriptions), (3) Where can I go? (answered by navigation, related links, next/previous). Good IA is invisible — users find content without noticing the structure. Poor IA drives users to support calls.'},
      {q:'What is the difference between a warning, a caution, and a note in technical documentation?',a:'These terms have specific safety hierarchy meanings (especially in aerospace and ANSI Z535): Danger = imminent fatal hazard (electric shock will kill you). Warning = potential serious injury or death if not followed. Caution = potential equipment damage without personal injury risk. Note/Notice = important information that doesn\'t affect safety. In DITA: &lt;note type="warning"&gt;, &lt;note type="caution"&gt;, &lt;note type="note"&gt;, &lt;note type="danger"&gt;. Safety notes must appear BEFORE the step they protect.'},
      {q:'Describe your SME interview process for gathering technical content.',a:'Before: research the topic thoroughly (read existing documentation, standards); prepare specific questions (not "tell me about X" but "I understand X works this way — is my understanding correct?"); send questions in advance; if possible, prepare a draft to review together. During: ask "show me" (observation reveals steps experts forget to verbalize); ask "why" (rationale helps write accurate, understandable content); ask about edge cases and what can go wrong; verify understanding ("So if this happens, the technician should...?"). After: transcribe notes immediately; identify gaps; follow up promptly with specific questions.'},
      {q:'What is the progressive disclosure principle in documentation?',a:'Progressive disclosure presents information in layers of increasing detail — overview first, details on demand. Readers get the key concept without being overwhelmed; those who need depth can access it. Implementation: short description (shortdesc) as overview layer; topic body as second layer; expandable sections, linked reference topics, or drill-down for maximum detail. Critical in online documentation where cognitive overload causes abandonment. DITA implements this through topic hierarchy in maps: parent topic = overview, child topics = details.'},
      {q:'How do you ensure technical accuracy in documentation you\'ve written?',a:'Multiple verification layers: (1) Self-review: read the procedure as if performing it for the first time — can I follow each step? Is anything ambiguous? (2) Technical review: send to the SME who knows the procedure. Ask specifically to verify steps, specifications, part numbers, and safety information. (3) Usability test: if possible, have a representative user (technician, engineer) attempt to follow the procedure — gaps and ambiguities emerge immediately. (4) Cross-reference with engineering drawings, specifications, and standards. (5) Version comparison: compare with previous approved revision for unintended changes.'},
      {q:'What is single sourcing?',a:'Single sourcing means maintaining content in one place and reusing it in multiple outputs or publications. Examples: a DITA conref that inserts the same warning in 50 tasks — one source, 50 uses; a topic referenced in both an AMM and a training guide; a keyref for a product name used across 200 topics; Markdown documentation served as both web site content and PDF. Benefits: update once, update everywhere; no inconsistency from forgetting to update all copies; reduced maintenance burden; lower localization cost.'},
      {q:'What is a content audit and when would you conduct one?',a:'A content audit systematically inventories and evaluates existing documentation: listing all documents, topics, or pages; assessing accuracy (is this still correct?), completeness (is anything missing?), currency (when was this last updated?), findability (can users find it?), and quality (is it clear and useful?). Conduct before: migrating to a new CMS or DITA; a major product update; responding to user complaints about documentation quality; or as a regular annual review. The audit output guides decisions about what to keep, update, consolidate, or retire.'},
      {q:'What is minimalism in technical writing?',a:'Minimalism (JoAnn Hackos / John Carroll) is a documentation philosophy: include only what users need; let users be active learners; support error recognition and recovery. Principles: action-oriented topics (not long tutorials); brief explanations (trust the user\'s knowledge); support real tasks (not product feature tours); include error recovery (what if this doesn\'t work?). In DITA: write the shortest possible shortdesc, the fewest steps that correctly complete the task, the minimum context needed — then stop. Minimalist documentation respects the user\'s time.'},
      {q:'How do you handle conflicting feedback from multiple reviewers?',a:'Acknowledge all feedback; group by type (factual corrections = high priority; style preferences = lower). For factual conflicts (both SMEs say different things): investigate further — check specifications, standards, engineering drawings. Escalate if needed. For style conflicts: apply the style guide; if the guide doesn\'t resolve it, make a judgment call and document it. Schedule a brief meeting with all reviewers if conflicts are significant. Never silently ignore reviewer feedback — acknowledge each comment, even if you\'re not implementing the suggestion, with a reason.'},
      {q:'What is the purpose of a documentation style guide?',a:'A style guide establishes conventions for consistency across a documentation set: terminology (use "select" not "click" for touchscreen interfaces), formatting (how to write warnings, notes, and cautions), naming (file naming conventions, heading style), tone (second person "you" or third person "the technician"), grammar choices (serial comma, singular they), and product-specific rules. For DITA: the style guide also specifies which topic type to use for which content, conref library conventions, profiling attribute vocabulary, and key naming standards.'},
      {q:'What is task-oriented documentation and how does it differ from feature-oriented?',a:'Feature-oriented documentation describes what a product has ("The hydraulic system includes three independent circuits"). Task-oriented documentation explains what users do ("How to depressurize the hydraulic system before maintenance"). Users typically arrive with a goal (they want to accomplish something) rather than a desire to learn about features. Task-oriented documentation: organizes by user task, uses DITA task topics, puts procedures front and center, and includes context only when it directly supports the task. Most AMM content is task-oriented; system descriptions are feature-oriented (concept topics).'},
      {q:'What does "audience analysis" mean in practice?',a:'Audience analysis identifies who will read the documentation and tailors content to their needs. In practice: interview stakeholders about who will use the documentation; observe representative users performing tasks; analyze support calls and tickets (what are users confused by?); review user training and certification requirements. Output: persona definition (role, expertise level, native language, reading environment, primary goal). Use personas to decide: vocabulary level, how much background knowledge to assume, which warnings are necessary, whether to include conceptual explanation or go straight to task.'},
      {q:'How do you write a good shortdesc for a task topic?',a:'A task shortdesc states the goal of the task in 1-2 sentences, focuses on the result (not the steps), and helps users decide whether this is the right topic for their situation. Formula: "[Imperative verb] [object] to [achieve goal] [when/why context]." Example: "Replace the main fuel filter to restore normal fuel flow after contamination or at scheduled maintenance intervals." Avoid: generic ("This topic describes..."), procedural ("Follow these steps to..."), or vague ("Important fuel filter information").'},
      {q:'What is the difference between editing and proofreading?',a:'Editing occurs before final content is established: substantive editing checks accuracy, completeness, structure, and clarity; copy editing checks grammar, usage, consistency, and style guide compliance. Proofreading is the final check on near-finished content ready for publication: checking for typos, formatting errors, page numbering, cross-reference correctness. In documentation workflows: technical review (accuracy) → editorial review (clarity, style) → copy edit (grammar, consistency) → proofread (final check). Skipping straight to proofreading without earlier editing stages produces polished but potentially inaccurate or unclear documentation.'},
      {q:'What is chunking in technical writing?',a:'Chunking is breaking content into small, scannable units that align with how human working memory processes information (typically 5-9 items maximum). Applied to documentation: short paragraphs (3-5 sentences maximum), use lists instead of comma-separated series, break long procedures into groups of 7-10 steps maximum (use sub-procedures), use headings to delineate topic boundaries, use callouts and tables to separate information types. Chunking improves scannability — users find specific information faster — and reduces cognitive load.'},
      {q:'How do you document a complex procedure with many conditional steps?',a:'Options depending on complexity: (1) Decision tree: present as a flowchart (Mermaid diagram or figure) showing the conditions and resulting paths. (2) Multiple tasks: create separate task topics for each path — "If condition A: Task X"; "If condition B: Task Y". Link them from a parent concept topic that explains the decision criteria. (3) Choices element: in DITA, use &lt;choices&gt; within a step for alternative options at a choice point. (4) If-then table: a reference table showing conditions and corresponding actions. Avoid deeply nested conditionals within a single linear procedure — they are hard to follow.'},
      {q:'What metrics indicate documentation quality?',a:'Quantitative: support ticket volume and resolution rate (do users call support for documentation-covered topics?); user satisfaction ratings; search query analysis (what are users searching for that they cannot find?); topic page bounce rate (do users immediately leave, suggesting wrong topic?). Qualitative: usability test success rate (can users complete tasks using only documentation?); SME review pass rate (how many errors per page in review?); readability scores (Flesch-Kincaid grade level). Track changes over time: quality improves when support tickets for documented topics decrease.'},
      {q:'What is the ATA iSpec2200 documentation standard?',a:'ATA iSpec2200 (Airlines for America Specification 2200) is the specification governing technical documentation for commercial aviation. It defines: the ATA chapter numbering system (ATA 21 = Air Conditioning through ATA 96), document types (AMM, CMM, IPC, WDM, SRM, SB), data module structure and content requirements, digital data delivery format (SGML/XML), and revision management practices. Understanding iSpec2200 is essential for anyone writing or managing commercial aviation maintenance documentation. DITA is compatible with iSpec2200 principles.'},
      {q:'How do you approach writing documentation for a product you know nothing about?',a:'(1) Gather existing documentation: previous versions, competitive products, standards. (2) Product immersion: use the product (if accessible) or observe others using it. (3) Structured SME interviews: start with system overview ("explain the product to me as if I\'m a user"), then specific procedures, then edge cases. (4) Draft and verify: write first drafts based on your understanding — incorrect drafts are efficient because SMEs correct errors faster than they explain from scratch. (5) Validate: have a representative user attempt the procedure. Technical writers are professional learners — not knowing a subject initially is normal and manageable.'},
      {q:'Describe the review cycle for safety-critical aerospace documentation.',a:'Safety-critical aerospace documentation (warnings, emergency procedures, safety-affecting maintenance tasks) requires multiple verification layers: (1) Technical review: qualified engineer or licensed technician verifies factual accuracy of every step and specification. (2) Safety review: safety engineer verifies completeness of hazard identification and adequacy of warnings. (3) QA review: technical editor verifies compliance with style guide and standards. (4) Regulatory/compliance review: for FAA/EASA-approved content, regulatory review for compliance. (5) Approval: formal sign-off required before publication. (6) Configuration control: release management ensures only current revision is in use. This cycle is longer but non-negotiable for safety-critical content.'},
      {q:'What is a documentation plan and what does it include?',a:'A documentation plan (also called a doc plan or documentation specification) defines scope and approach for a documentation project before writing begins. Contents: project overview and objectives; audience definition; document types and deliverables; scope (what\'s in, what\'s out); topic list and preliminary structure; authoring tools and standards; review process and milestones; delivery format and publication method; resource requirements; schedule with milestones; risks and mitigation. A doc plan prevents scope creep and aligns stakeholder expectations before significant writing investment is made.'},
    ]
  },
  oxygen: {
    label:'Oxygen XML',
    icon:'⚗️',
    questions:[
      {q:'What are the three editing views in Oxygen XML Editor?',a:'Author view: visual, CSS-styled editing mode where XML tags are hidden or shown as markers — similar to a word processor. Best for content entry and editing. Text view: raw XML source with syntax highlighting, folding, and content completion. Best for direct XML editing, debugging, and complex attribute work. Grid view: tree/table representation of the XML structure. Best for viewing element hierarchy and batch attribute editing. Switch with Ctrl+T or the view tabs at the bottom of the editor.'},
      {q:'How do you open a DITA map in Oxygen\'s DITA Maps Manager?',a:'Three methods: (1) Open the .ditamap file (double-click in Project panel or File > Open) — Oxygen prompts to open it in DITA Maps Manager; click Yes. (2) Right-click the .ditamap in Project panel > Open in DITA Maps Manager. (3) If already open in editor: DITA Maps Manager > click the Open Map button and browse to the file. The Maps Manager displays the topic hierarchy and provides controls for adding, reordering, and managing topics.'},
      {q:'How do you create and run a DITA transformation scenario in Oxygen?',a:'(1) Open root map in DITA Maps Manager. (2) Click the Configure Transformation Scenarios button (wrench icon) or Document > Transformation > Configure Transformation Scenarios. (3) Click New > DITA OT Transformation. (4) Enter a name, set the transtype (pdf2, html5, webhelp-responsive, etc.). (5) On the Filters tab: browse to a DITAVAL file for conditional processing. (6) On Output tab: set output directory. (7) Add custom parameters if needed. (8) OK. (9) Apply Associated (to save). (10) Run (play button) to publish.'},
      {q:'What is Oxygen\'s "Validate and Check for Completeness" and what does it check?',a:'Available from DITA Maps Manager by right-clicking the root map: Validate > Validate and Check for Completeness. It runs DITA-specific validation: checks all topicref href paths exist (files present); verifies all conref addresses resolve to existing elements; confirms all keyref keys are defined in the context map; detects duplicate topic IDs across the publication; validates all xref cross-references resolve. Run before every transformation — fix all errors to ensure publishing succeeds and output is consistent.'},
      {q:'What is the Oxygen Content Completion Assistant and how do you invoke it?',a:'The Content Completion Assistant is Oxygen\'s context-aware element/attribute suggestion popup. In Author view: press Enter or Ctrl+Space at the cursor position to see valid elements. In Text view: Ctrl+Space after < shows valid element names; Ctrl+Space inside a tag after a space shows valid attribute names; Ctrl+Space after = shows valid attribute values (for constrained attributes like type). The assistant only suggests elements valid at the current location (based on the DITA DTD) — this prevents structural errors.'},
      {q:'How do you insert a conref using Oxygen\'s Reuse panel?',a:'Open the Reuse panel (Window > Show View > Reuse or use the View menu). The panel provides browse-based conref insertion: navigate to the source file, select the source element, drag it to the insertion point or click Insert. Alternatively: in Text view, type the conref attribute directly (conref="path/file.dita#topicid/elementid"). Or: in Author view, in the Attributes panel, type the conref attribute value. After inserting, validate to confirm the conref resolves.'},
      {q:'What is a "context map" in Oxygen?',a:'The context map (also called root map) is the DITA map currently open in the DITA Maps Manager. It defines the key space used for keyref resolution while authoring. When you edit a topic, Oxygen resolves keyrefs against the key definitions in the context map — showing the correct product name, specifications, etc. as you write. If the wrong map is set as context, keyrefs may not resolve or resolve to incorrect values. Set the context map: open the desired map in DITA Maps Manager and set it as the main map.'},
      {q:'How do you perform a project-wide find and replace in Oxygen?',a:'Find/Replace (Ctrl+H) with the "In files" option enabled searches across all files in a scope (project, directory, or open files). Key options: Enable "Regular Expression" for pattern matching; "XPath in results" to scope replacement to specific XML elements (e.g., replace only in &lt;p&gt; elements); "Only in selected file types" to limit to .dita files. Warning: project-wide replace is powerful — review matches before replacing. Oxygen shows a preview of all matches. Always commit to Git before a large-scale replace so you can revert if needed.'},
      {q:'What does Oxygen\'s "Format and Indent" do and when should you use it?',a:'Format and Indent (Ctrl+Shift+F in Text view) reformats the XML source with consistent indentation — every element on its own line, correct nesting indentation. Use after: pasting XML from another source (often arrives as a single line); when the file has inconsistent indentation making it hard to read; before committing to Git (consistent formatting reduces diff noise). Note: DITA is whitespace-significant in some elements — Format and Indent may add whitespace to text content. Use with awareness; some teams disable it in team settings.'},
      {q:'What is Oxygen\'s track changes feature and how is it used in documentation review?',a:'Oxygen Author view supports XML track changes (Edit > Track Changes > Record Changes). When enabled: text additions are underlined and colored; deletions are struck through. Reviewers can add inline comments. Authors can: accept a change (Ctrl+Shift+A), reject a change (remove the suggested change), or use the Track Changes toolbar to accept/reject all. This enables a structured review workflow where a technical editor\'s markup is visible to the author before acceptance. Works on DITA XML — changes are tracked at the XML element level.'},
      {q:'How do you create a new DITA topic from a template in Oxygen?',a:'File > New (Ctrl+N) > New Document > Framework Templates > DITA > [topic type: Concept, Task, Reference, etc.]. Oxygen creates the file with the correct DOCTYPE declaration, root element, and boilerplate structure. Better: File > New > New from Template to use custom team templates (if configured). Alternatively: right-click in the DITA Maps Manager on the parent topicref > Append Child > New DITA Topic, which creates the file AND adds a topicref to the map automatically.'},
      {q:'What is Oxygen\'s Safe Delete feature?',a:'Safe Delete (right-click > Refactoring > Safe Delete on a file in Project panel) checks all references to a topic file before deletion. It reports: every topicref in every map that references this file; every conref that points to an element in this file; every xref that links to this file. Only proceed if all references are intentional (maps being deleted too) or you have removed the references first. Prevents orphaned references. The non-safe alternative (Delete key in OS) simply removes the file, leaving broken references.'},
      {q:'How do you validate a DITA topic against a custom Schematron in Oxygen?',a:'(1) Create or obtain the Schematron file (.sch). (2) In Oxygen Preferences > Document Type Association > DITA (or your document type) > Validation tab: add the Schematron file as an additional validation file. (3) Validation runs automatically on save or with Ctrl+Shift+V. Schematron results appear alongside DTD validation errors. Alternatively: Document > Validate > Validate with Schema and browse to the Schematron. Schematron checks business rules that DTD cannot express (shortdesc presence, forbidden words, required metadata completeness).'},
      {q:'What is the Oxygen Large Files Editor and when would you use it?',a:'Oxygen has a specialized mode for very large XML files (hundreds of MB) that cannot be fully loaded into memory. Enable via: Options > Preferences > Editor > Large File Editing. It loads a text streaming parser view rather than a full DOM. Features: incremental loading, streaming search, streaming display. In practice: DITA topics should never be large enough to require this (one topic per file is typically small). Large file editing is relevant for: large DITA-OT generated intermediate files, very large XML databases, or legacy monolithic XML documents being migrated to DITA.'},
      {q:'What Oxygen keyboard shortcut runs DITA-specific validation?',a:'Ctrl+Shift+V runs full document validation (including DTD/XSD validation and Schematron if configured). For DITA Maps Manager completeness check: no single keyboard shortcut — right-click the root map > Validate > Validate and Check for Completeness. Ctrl+Shift+W runs well-formedness check only (checks XML syntax without schema validation — faster but less thorough). Configure custom keyboard shortcuts in Options > Menu Shortcut Keys. Many teams add a shortcut for "Transform with scenario" (default Ctrl+Shift+T) for one-key publishing.'},
      {q:'How do you manage multiple transformation scenarios for different output formats and variants?',a:'In Configure Transformation Scenarios, create one scenario per output format + variant combination: "Product A — PDF for Review", "Product A — HTML5 for Web", "Product B — PDF Final", etc. Associate the scenario with the map: select and click "Apply Associated." The play button then runs the associated scenario. For batch transformation: select multiple scenarios in Configure dialog and run them all. Store scenario definitions in the Oxygen project file (.xpr) committed to Git so all team members share the same publishing configurations.'},
      {q:'What is the Oxygen Project panel and how does it help DITA teams?',a:'The Project panel (View > Show View > Project) is a file browser for your DITA project directory. Unlike the OS file manager, it understands the project context. Features: right-click any .dita file to open, find references, check in/out (if CCMS integrated), or add to a DITA map. Right-click the project root to configure project-level settings. Save the project as an .xpr file (File > Project > Save Project As) — the .xpr stores project paths, transformation scenarios, and validation scenarios. Share the .xpr file via Git for consistent team settings.'},
      {q:'What does the Outline view in Oxygen show?',a:'The Outline view (View > Show View > Outline) shows a structured tree of the current topic\'s XML element hierarchy. In Author view: shows the rendered content structure. In Text view: shows the exact XML element tree. Use it to: navigate to any element quickly (click an element to jump there); see the current element\'s ancestors (breadcrumb); move elements by drag-and-drop in the tree. For large topics, the Outline is essential for navigation. In DITA Maps Manager: the outline shows the publication\'s topic hierarchy.'},
      {q:'How do you configure Oxygen to use a specific DITA-OT version?',a:'Options > Preferences > XML > DITA > DITA Open Toolkit location. Oxygen bundles its own DITA-OT; you can also point to an externally installed DITA-OT (with additional plugins). Change the DITA-OT version to: use a newer DITA-OT than Oxygen ships; use custom plugins not included in the bundled version; match the version used in your CI/CD pipeline for identical output. After changing, restart Oxygen. Check the installed version: DITA-OT info appears in the Oxygen About dialog.'},
      {q:'What is the Oxygen Author view "Tags Display Mode" setting?',a:'Tags Display Mode controls how XML tags appear in Author view. Options: No Tags (fully hidden — pure visual mode); Partial Tags (block elements shown, inline hidden); Block Tags (all block-level elements visible); Show All Tags (both block and inline); Full Tags with Attributes (all tags + attributes — most verbose). Toggle via Document > Author > Tags Display Mode menu. For general content writing: Partial Tags. For debugging structure or attribute-heavy work: Full Tags with Attributes. Ctrl+Shift+P is the default shortcut to toggle through modes.'},
      {q:'How do you search for DITA topics containing a specific conref source in Oxygen?',a:'Find/Replace (Ctrl+H) with: "In files" scope set to your project directory; "Regular Expression" enabled; search pattern: conref=".*warnings-library\\.dita (or the specific source file). This lists all files referencing the source. Alternatively: right-click the source file in Project panel > Find References: Oxygen automatically searches all project files for references to this file via topicref, xref, and conref. The results appear in the Results panel with file path and line number.'},
    ]
  },
};
